{{other uses}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2016}} {{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}} {{Infobox character | image = File:Anjani with Child Hanuman - Bronze - Pallava Period - ACCN 15-524 - Government Museum - Mathura 2013-02-24 6603.JPG | alt = Anjani | caption = Anjani with Child Hanuman (Bronze - Pallava Period). | spouse = [[Kesari (Ramayana)|Kesari]] | children = [[Hanuman]] }}
'''{{IAST|Añjanā}}''' ('''Anchanai''', '''Anjani''', '''Anjati''', '''Anjaneya''' or '''Swaha''') is the mother of Lord [[Hanuman]], one of the heroes of the Indian epic, the ''[[Ramayana]]''.
According to a version of the legend, {{IAST|Añjanā}} was an [[apsara]] named ''Puñjikastalā'', who was born on earth as a [[vanara]] princess and married [[Kesari (Ramayana)|Kesari]], a [[vanara]] chief. [[Vayu]], god of the wind, carried the divine power of [[Lord Shiva]] to Anjana's womb, and thus Hanuman was born as an incarnation of Lord Shiva.<ref>{{cite book | last =Pollet | first =Gilbert | title =Indian Epic Values: Ramayana and Its Impact: Proceedings of the 8th International Ramayana Conference, Leuven, 6–8 July 1991 (Orientalia Lovaniensia Analecta) | publisher =Peeters | date =January 1995 | isbn =978-90-6831-701-5 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=India through the ages|last=Gopal|first=Madan|year= 1990| page= 68|editor=K.S. Gautam|publisher=Publication Division, Ministry of Information and Broadcasting, Government of India}}</ref>
In [[Himachal Pradesh]], Goddess Anjana is worshiped as a family deity. There is a temple dedicated to her at 'Masrer' near [[Dharamshala]]. It is believed that Sri Anjana once came and remained there for some time. One of the locals upon learning, revealed her real identity to the other villagers, going against her wishes. She soon left, but not before turning that villager into stone which remains outside her temple even to this day. Her [[vahana]] (vehicle) is a scorpion, hence believers worship Anjana after being bitten by a scorpion.{{citation needed|date=July 2017}}
There is a cave of Anjana Devi near Hunasigi (Talikota) not very far from Hampi (Kishkinda) where it is belived Hanuman was born.
