[[File:AbaqaOnHorseArghunStandingGhazanAsAChild.jpg|thumb|Mongol rulers [[Arghun]] and [[Abaqa]] were Buddhists. From the 14th century ''Universal History'' by [[Rashid-al-Din Hamadani]].]]
'''Buddhism in Iran''' dates back to the [[2nd century]], when [[Parthian Empire|Parthians]], such as [[An Shigao]], were active in spreading [[Buddhism in China]]. Many of the earliest translators of Buddhist literature into Chinese were from [[Parthia]] and other kingdoms linked with present-day [[Iran]].<ref>{{citation|title=Handbuch der Orientalistik: Sarvāstivāda Buddhist Scholasticism|publisher=Brill|first=Charles|last=Willemen|first2=Bart|last2=Dessein|first3=Collett|last3=Cox|first4=Jan|last4=Gonda|first5=Johannes|last5=Bronkhorst|authorlink5=Johannes Bronkhorst |first6=Bertold|last6=Spuler|first7=Hartwig|last7=Altenmüller|pages=128–130|isbn=978-90-04-10231-6}}</ref>

==History==

===Pre-Islamic Iran===
Buddhists were persecuted during the [[Sasanid]] rule in the vast territory they ruled, as they made [[Zoroastrianism]] the state religion in 224 AD, and thereafter burned many Buddhist sites in the regions where it was practised, namely [[Central Asia]]. Surviving Buddhist sites in the easternmost Sassanian territories comprising modern day Central Asia were later raided in the 5th century by the [[Hephthalite Empire|White Huns]].<ref name="Yarshater1993">{{cite book|author=[[Ehsan Yarshater]]|title=The Cambridge History of Iran|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y7IHmyKcPtYC&pg=PA956|year=1993|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-24693-4|pages=956–7}}</ref>

===Arab conquests and decline===
At the time of the [[Arab conquests]] in the mid-7th century, much of the eastern Iranian world was mainly Buddhist. [[Afghanistan]] is rich in Buddhist sites; others have been found in [[Turkmenistan]], [[Uzbekistan]], [[Tajikistan]], and within Iran itself.<ref>[[Richard Foltz]], "Buddhism in the Iranian World," ''The Muslim World'' 100/2-3, 2010, pp. 204-214</ref> The Arab conquests brought the final demise of Buddhism in Eastern Iran and Afghanistan, although in some sites like [[Bamiyan]] and [[Hadda, Afghanistan|Hadda]] it survived until the 8th or 9th century.<ref name="Yarshater1993"/>

[[Mongol]] ruler [[Ghazan]], who received Buddhist education in his youth, converted to [[Islam]] in 1295 AD and made it the state religion of the [[Ilkhanate]].<ref>{{Citation | last =  Dunn | first = Ross E. | title = The adventures of Ibn Battuta, a Muslim traveler of the fourteenth century | publisher = University of California Press | year = 2005 | location = | pages = 86, 161 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=Js8qHFVw2gEC&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&q= | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-0-520-24385-9}}</ref> He also prohibited the practice of Buddhism, but allowed monks to go into exile into neighboring Buddhist regions.<ref name="AkasoyBurnett2011">{{cite book|author1=Anna Akasoy|author2=Charles Burnett|author3=Ronit Yoeli-Tlalim|title=Islam and Tibet: Interactions Along the Musk Routes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZfWXIfbynwYC&pg=PA10|year=2011|publisher=Ashgate Publishing, Ltd.|isbn=978-0-7546-6956-2|pages=10–11}}</ref>

===Contemporary===
In recent years, as part of the post-revolution period, Buddhist ideas and practice, as part of a broader reemergence of various faiths in [[Iran]], has experienced an upsurge of interest among [[Iranian people|Iranians]]. Some of the poetry of [[Sohrab Sepehri]] shows Buddhist influence.<ref>Foltz, pp. 212-213</ref>

