[[File:Zomba Mosque 1.jpg|thumb|right|180px|A [[mosque]] in [[Zomba, Malawi|Zomba]]]]
{{islam by country}} '''[[Islam]]''' is the second largest religion in '''[[Malawi]]''' after [[Christianity]]. Nearly all of Malawi's [[Muslim]]s adhere to [[Sunni Islam]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Klaus Fiedler|title=Conflicted Power in Malawian Christianity: Essays Missionary and Evangelical from Malawi|date=2015|publisher=Mzuni Press|isbn=9789990802498|pages=180-1|edition=illustrated}}</ref> Though difficult to assess,<ref>{{cite book|author1=Arne S. Steinforth|title=Troubled Minds: On the Cultural Construction of Mental Disorder and Normality in Southern Malawi|date=2009|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783631587171|page=79}}</ref> according to the [[CIA Factbook]], in 2008 about 12.8% of the country's population was Muslim;<ref>[https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/mi.html CIA statistics]</ref> such a lower figure is rejected by Muslim organisations in the country,<ref>{{cite book|author1=[[Owen J. M. Kalinga]]|title=Historical Dictionary of Malawi|date=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780810859616|page=202|edition=revised}}</ref> who claim a figure of 30-35% (which is described as "wishful thinking" by Christian missionaries).<ref>{{cite book|author1=Klaus Fiedler|title=Conflicted Power in Malawian Christianity: Essays Missionary and Evangelical from Malawi|date=2015|publisher=Mzuni Press|isbn=9789990802498|page=213|edition=illustrated}}</ref> According to the Malawi Religion Project<ref>{{cite web|url=http://malawi.pop.upenn.edu/malawi-data-qualitative-religion |title=The Malawi Religion Project (MRP) &#124; Malawi Longitudinal Study of Families and Health (MLSFH) |publisher=Malawi.pop.upenn.edu |date= |accessdate=31 December 2013}}</ref> run by the University of Pennsylvania, in 2010 approximately 25% of the population was Muslim, concentrated mostly in the [[Southern Region, Malawi|Southern Region]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://repository.upenn.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1045&context=psc_working_papers |title=Cohort Profile: The Malawi Longitudinal Study of Families and Health (MLSFH) |author=HANS-PETER KOHLER |website=Repository.upenn.edu |accessdate=2016-02-09}}</ref>
==History== Islam arrived in Malawi with the [[Arab]] and [[Swahili people|Swahili]] traders who traded in ivory, gold and later on slaves beginning from 16th century to the 19th century. It is also argued that Islam first arrived in Malawi through traders from the [[Kilwa Sultanate]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Arne S. Steinforth|title=Troubled Minds: On the Cultural Construction of Mental Disorder and Normality in Southern Malawi|date=2009|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783631587171|page=78}}</ref> Two Muslim teachers, Shayhks Abdallah Mkwanda and Sabiti Ngaunje, also played an important role in the spread of Islam.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Owen J. M. Kalinga|title=Historical Dictionary of Malawi|date=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780810859616|page=200|edition=revised}}</ref> According to [[UNESCO]], the first mosque was built by Swahili-Arab ivory traders.<ref>http://whc.unesco.org/en/tentativelists/5603/</ref>
During the [[History of Malawi#British rule|colonial era]], the authorities in the country feared that Islam posed the greatest threat, as an ideology of resistance, to their rule.<ref>{{cite book|author1=John McCracken|title=A History of Malawi, 1859-1966|date=2012|publisher=Boydell & Brewer Ltd|isbn=9781847010506|page=142|edition=illustrated}}</ref> This view was shared by Christian missionaries, who greatly feared that Islam could unite Africans in hostilities and uprisings against colonial rule.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Owen J. M. Kalinga|title=Historical Dictionary of Malawi|date=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780810859616|page=201|edition=revised}}</ref>
The 1970s witnessed the start of an Islamic revival among Muslims in Malawi, as well as among Muslims across the globe.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Klaus Fiedler|title=Conflicted Power in Malawian Christianity: Essays Missionary and Evangelical from Malawi|date=2015|publisher=Mzuni Press|isbn=9789990802498|page=202|edition=illustrated}}</ref> Recently, Muslim groups have engaged in [[Dawah|missionary work]] in Malawi. Much of this is performed by the [[African Muslim Agency]], based in [[Kuwait]]. The Kuwait-sponsored AMA has translated the [[Qur'an]] into [[Chichewa language|Chichewa]] (Cinyanja),<ref>[http://www.frontline.org.za/mission%20reports_prayer/macedonian_call_Malawi.htm Proseletysation in Malawi]</ref> one of the official languages of Malawi, and has engaged in other missionary work in the country. There are thought to be about 800 [[jumu'ah]] mosques in the country, with at least one or two to be found in nearly every town.<ref>{{cite book|author1=David Mphande|title=Oral Literature and Moral Education among the Lakeside Tonga of Northern Malawi|date=2014|publisher=Mzuni Press|isbn=9789990802443|page=132|edition=illustrated, reprint}}</ref> There are also several Islamic schools<ref>[http://www.islamicfinder.org/cityPrayer.php?country=Malawi Islamic organisations in Malawi]</ref> and a broadcasting station called Radio Islam.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Harri Englund|title=Christianity and Public Culture in Africa|date=2011|publisher=Ohio University Press|isbn=9780821443668|page=168}}</ref> A major Muslim center of learning exists in Mpemba, outside of [[Blantyre]], funded mainly by money from [[Saudi Arabia]] and Kuwait.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Owen J. M. Kalinga|title=Historical Dictionary of Malawi|date=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780810859616|page=201|edition=revised}}</ref>
==Demography== A large number of Muslims in Malawi come from the [[Yao people (East Africa)|Yao people]],<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Brenner|editor1-first=Louis|title=Muslim Identity and Social Change in Sub-Saharan Africa|date=1993|publisher=Indiana University Press|isbn=9780253312716|page=79|edition=illustrated}}</ref> who are described as "the most important source of Islam in the country".<ref>{{cite book|author1=Timothy Insoll|title=The Archaeology of Islam in Sub-Saharan Africa|date=2003|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=9780521657020|page=393|edition=illustrated}}</ref> Even before their conversion to Islam, many Yao chiefs used Swahili Muslims as scribes and advisers.<ref>{{cite book|author1=I. C. Lamba|title=Contradictions in Post-war Education Policy Formulation and Application in Colonial Malawi 1945-1961: A Historical Study of the Dynamics of Colonial Survival|date=2010|publisher=African Books Collective|isbn=9789990887945|page=154}}</ref> As a result of their strong trading contacts with Swahili-Arabs, many Yao adopted Islam and the two groups often intermarried.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Owen J. M. Kalinga|title=Historical Dictionary of Malawi|date=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780810859616|page=155|edition=revised}}</ref> The Yao form the largest majority south and east of [[Lake Malawi]].<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Naʻīm|editor1-first=ʻAbd Allāh Aḥmad|title=Islamic Family Law in A Changing World: A Global Resource Book|date=2002|publisher=[[Zed Books]]|isbn=9781842770931|page=189|edition=illustrated}}</ref> Muslims can also be found among other groups, such as the lakeside [[Chewa people]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Owen J. M. Kalinga|title=Historical Dictionary of Malawi|date=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780810859616|page=200|edition=revised}}</ref> and Indian<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Naʻīm|editor1-first=ʻAbd Allāh Aḥmad|title=Islamic Family Law in A Changing World: A Global Resource Book|date=2002|publisher=[[Zed Books]]|isbn=9781842770931|page=194|edition=illustrated}}</ref> and other Asian Malawians.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Arne S. Steinforth|title=Troubled Minds: On the Cultural Construction of Mental Disorder and Normality in Southern Malawi|date=2009|publisher=Peter Lang|isbn=9783631587171|page=79}}</ref> Muslims in the country have been described as a "vocal and powerful community."<ref>{{cite book|author1=Owen J. M. Kalinga|title=Historical Dictionary of Malawi|date=2012|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=9780810859616|page=201|edition=revised}}</ref> ==Notable Muslims== An important Malawian Muslim is [[Bakili Muluzi]], the first freely elected President of Malawi from 1994 to 2004.
