[[Islam]] in [[South Ossetia]] is presented by migrants who work there, but not by the native Ossetians, unlike in North Ossetia - Alania.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-18269214|title=South Ossetia profile|publisher=[[BBC]]|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>

== History ==
Islam started to spread in Ossetia in the 14th and 15th centuries. According to sources, mostly high noble families of Ossetian society received Muslim religion and peasants remained into the Christian faith.{{fact|date=September 2017}}

“In the 17th and 18th centuries, part of Ossetian people from [[Digor, Kars|Digor]] (under influence of [[Kabarday]]) received Islam religion. However, Islam was transpassed by christianity during the reign of the [[Russian Empire]] in Ossetia since 1801.<ref>[http://religiebi.info/index.php?a=main&pid=89&lang=eng Religious Identity of Ossetian People]</ref> In fact, according to Ruslan Bzargov:"In Ossetia Muslims never had more than 12-15% of the population"<ref>http://osetia.info/articles/2455/</ref>{{clarify|date=September 2017}}

== Demographics ==
Although there are no official censuses, estimates say that about 0.5% of the population of South Ossetia are Muslims. Officials also suspect that Russia's military and political actions will likely cause this percentage to increase.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freerepublic.com/focus/f-news/2074978/posts|title=Muslims Seen Moving into Abkhazia and South Ossetia, Changing Religious Balance in Both|date=September 3, 2008|accessdate=22 September 2017}}</ref>{{reliable|date=September 2017}}

